---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import siteData from '../data/site.json';

const page = siteData.pages.books;
const styles = [
  'assets/css/tokens.css',
  'assets/css/interior-base.css',
  'assets/css/layout.css',
  'assets/css/components.css',
  'assets/css/books.css',
];
---
<Base
  title={page.title}
  description={page.description}
  canonical={page.canonical}
  subtitle={page.subtitle}
  eyebrow={page.eyebrow}
  introKicker={page.introKicker}
  introTitle={page.introTitle}
  introText={page.introText}
  currentNav={page.currentNav}
  brandMode="editorial"
  styles={styles}
>
  <div class="stack">
    <section class="reading-width stack" aria-label="Publishing programs">
      <article class="card stack">
        <h2 class="section-heading">SEXP</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">Original fiction, poetry, novella, and hybrid work. Books that do not require the trade apparatus to make their case. SEXP selects for formal pressure, tonal command, and the kind of spiritual seriousness that survives direct encounter. Not regional color. Not pastoral consolation. Not the workshop aesthetic that has hollowed out American fiction for decades. Very few entries.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="card stack">
        <h2 class="section-heading">Library of the Southern Civilization</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">Not antiquarianism. The Southern tradition has been systematically misfiled: by Northern editorial taste, by academic rehabilitation programs that defang what they canonize, and by commercial publishing that cannot tell the difference between a live inheritance and a dead curio. The Library recovers texts that deserve continued circulation and returns them in editions that treat them as live ammunition.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="card stack">
        <h2 class="section-heading">Translation</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">The logic behind the selection is simple: these traditions have preserved formal and spiritual registers that Anglo-American publishing has spent decades flattening. The series brings across what has been allowed to remain difficult, without apology, without domestication, and without the translator's note that explains away the difficulty before the reader can feel it.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="card stack">
        <h2 class="section-heading">What comes next</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">The catalog funds what follows. RICE Magazine, the fellowship mechanism, and the broader Commonsplace horizon only become real if the books first accumulate enough weight to support them. That sequence is deliberate.</p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <nav class="filter-tabs" id="books-filter" aria-label="Filter by series"></nav>
    <div class="helper-text" id="books-status" role="status" aria-live="polite">Loading catalog...</div>
    <section class="books-list" id="books-list" aria-label="Books catalog"></section>
    <div class="reading-width">
      <div class="catalog-actions">
        <a class="button" href="/submit">Submission inquiries</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href="/about">Rights or press inquiries</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Fragment slot="scripts">
    <script is:inline src="/assets/js/site-shell.js" type="module"></script>
    <script is:inline src="/assets/js/books-page.js" type="module"></script>
  </Fragment>
</Base>
